{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445416000,"nonce":"ckzIo7J4pWn8cDAFA/HesJ8+1cw=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTgxNTQ5OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/345#issuecomment-149815499"},"message":"\u003e Downloads disappear, get renamed, etc. We cannot rely on externally controlled URLs for longevity. Bad URLs are a continuous issue for us\n\nSo true! Not to mention the possibility that files get modified if no checksums are being used\n\n\u003e in lieu of requests like https://package-server/?url=https://... we'll make requests like https://package-server/path/to/dir/shaaaa256suuuuum#https://the-real-url, appending the real url as a URL fragment to the end (ignored on serving files) in order to preserve some end-user transparency of which files are being downloaded.\n\nI actually prefer the first solution, and do something like:\n\nhttps://package-server/get/?url=https://\nhttps://package-server/checksum/?url=https:// or https://package-server/sig/?url=https:// and obtain Pgp signatures\nhttps://package-server/timestamp/?url=https:// (not neccesairy if Pgp signatures are used)\n\nI think the HTML comment suffix is a bit hacky. It requires to add these #https:// suffixes to each url within every galaxy wrapper but leaving them out can't break the system (these suffixes are never passed through to a server). Because it doesn't break when it's missing it probably get's used less frequently over time, unless planemo will be modified. I don't think html suffixes are designed for this purpose.\n\n\u003e in lieu of an actual proxy, the script just downloads the URLs to files named after their sha256sum, and lets nginx/etc serve them up.\n\n(I am not sure if I understand this correctly, but I suppose you mean that files are being accessed by their sha256sum?)\n\nIf so, this implies that hash collisions will never take place ;) To me it would be easier to understand code like this:\n\n```\n\u003cpackage\u003ehttps://galaxy-proxy-server/get/?url=http://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/grep/grep-2.4.tar.gz\u003c/package\u003e\n```\n\nInstead of:\n\n```\n\u003cpackage\u003ehttps://galaxy-proxy-server/a32032bab36208509466654df12f507600dfe0313feebbcd218c32a70bf72a16/#http://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/grep/grep-2.4.tar.gz\u003c/package\u003e\n```\n\nwhereas:\n\n```\n\u003cpackage\u003ehttps://galaxy-proxy-server/a32032bab36208509466654df12f507600dfe0313feebbcd218c32a70bf72a16/\u003c/package\u003e\n```\n\nwill work too.\n\nLooking forward to this!","files":null}]}